i## Adjustments for Campus Network Environment		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iAs mentioned in the		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iprevious article		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i, my university provides one wired network and two Wi-Fi networks with		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ithese characteristics:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i1. Wired network: 1.5M speed limit, web-based login, accessible by		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   other devices on the LAN		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i2. Wireless network: 1.5M speed limit, web-based login, inaccessible		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   to other wireless devices (Wi-Fi isolation, still accessible via		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   wired connection)		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i3. eduroam: No speed limit, WPA2 Enterprise login, inaccessible to		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   other wireless devices (Wi-Fi isolation, still accessible via wired		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   connection)		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iSince the Raspberry Pi has both wired and wireless NICs, the optimal		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
isetup is:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- Raspberry Pi uses eduroam for PT downloads		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- I manage it via the wired NIC's IP from my computer		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iBut if you connect both interfaces simultaneously, you'll notice only		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ione NIC has traffic — the other can't even ping. This happens because		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iwhen the Linux kernel receives a connection request (e.g., TCP SYN),		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iit doesn't "return via the same path." Instead, it uses the routing		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
itable to decide which NIC to respond from. This causes responses from		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ithe wireless NIC to be sent for requests arriving via the wired NIC,		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iwhich get dropped due to isolation policies or IP mismatches.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iWe need policy routing to enforce "return via the incoming path."		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iPolicy routing directs packets matching specific conditions (e.g.,		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iarriving via a certain NIC) to a dedicated routing table instead of		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ithe main one. I used this before in "		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iConfiguring Hurricane Electric IPv6 Tunnel on OpenVZ, Enabling Full		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iAddress Pool with Native IPv6		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i." Though that was for IPv6, Linux's IPv4/IPv6 commands are similar —		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ijust tweak as needed.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iFirst, check routes with `route` :		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  Kernel IP routing table		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  Destination     Gateway         Genmask         Flags Metric Ref    Use Iface		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  default         10.106.65.1     0.0.0.0         UG    202    0        0 eth0		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  default         10.107.128.1    0.0.0.0         UG    303    0        0 wlan0		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  10.106.65.0     0.0.0.0         255.255.255.0   U     400    0        0 eth0		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  10.107.128.0    0.0.0.0         255.255.240.0   U     303    0        0 wlan0		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iNote the two default routes:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- eth0 (wired) gateway: 10.106.65.1		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- wlan0 (wireless) gateway: 10.107.128.1		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iThen check IPs with `ip addr` :		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  [...]		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  2: eth0: [...]		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      inet 10.106.65.213/24 [...]		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  3: wlan0: [...]		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      inet 10.107.134.208/20 [...]		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iKey details:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- Wired IP: 10.106.65.213/24 → Subnet: 10.106.65.0/24		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- Wireless IP: 10.107.134.208/20 → Subnet: 10.107.128.0/20		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iEdit `/etc/iproute2/rt_tables` to add dedicated routing tables:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  [...]		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  # Add these at the end:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  100    university_eth		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  101    university_wlan		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iSet up policy routing:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  # Route university_eth traffic via wired gateway		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  ip route add default via 10.106.65.1 dev eth0 table university_eth		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  # Route university_wlan traffic via wireless gateway		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  ip route add default via 10.107.128.1 dev wlan0 table university_wlan		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  # Route packets FROM wired subnet to university_eth table		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  ip rule add from 10.106.65.0/24 table university_eth		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  # Route packets FROM wireless subnet to university_wlan table		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  ip rule add from 10.107.128.0/20 table university_wlan		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iAdd these four commands to `/etc/rc.local` for auto-start. If they		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
